1. Performance
• 	The system must handle multiple simultaneous users without significant delays.
• 	Response time for critical operations (e.g., placing an order, updating inventory) should be less than 2 seconds.
• 	The system must support at least 100 concurrent users in a medium-sized restaurant environment.


2. Reliability
• 	The system must ensure high availability (uptime of at least 99%).
• 	It must recover gracefully from unexpected failures and provide error messages to users.
• 	Data integrity must be maintained even in case of system crashes.


3. Usability
• 	The interface must be intuitive and easy to use for non-technical staff.
• 	Navigation should be simple, with clear menus and role-based dashboards.
• 	Training time for new staff should not exceed 2 hours.


4. Security
• 	The system must enforce authentication and role-based access control.
• 	Sensitive data (e.g., customer information, financial reports) must be encrypted.
• 	The system must log all critical actions (e.g., inventory changes, staff schedule updates).


5. Scalability
• 	The system must be able to expand to support larger restaurants or chains.
• 	It should allow integration with external systems (e.g., supplier APIs, online reservation platforms).
• 	Database design must support growth in data volume without performance degradation.


6. Maintainability
• 	The system must be modular to allow easy updates and bug fixes.
• 	Documentation must be provided for developers and administrators.
• 	Code should follow standard conventions to ensure readability and long-term support.


7. Portability
• 	The system must run on multiple platforms (Windows, Linux, macOS).
• 	It should be accessible via web browsers and mobile devices.
• 	Migration to another database or hosting environment should be possible with minimal effort.
